# Fluff Date: 2026-02-20 17:30:00
overview:<p>The Tsunami is a medium BattleMech designed and manufactured by OmniTech Industries on Solaris VII. Introduced in the early 3050s as OmniTech's flagship design, the forty-ton machine was intended to serve both on the competitive Solaris arena circuit and as a capable battlefield combatant for minor mercenary commands. Well designed but broadly considered unimpressive by critics, the Tsunami nonetheless carved out a steady niche among Solaris stables and small mercenary outfits over the following decade and a half. OmniTech's relatively low production rate kept the design from achieving widespread distribution, but the advent of newer technologies allowed the company to revitalize the platform with an upgraded model that offered greater versatility for both arena gladiators and battlefield operators alike. The lessons learned from the Tsunami's mixed reception would later inform OmniTech's development of the heavier Morpheus arena fighter.</p>

capabilities:<p>The upgraded TS-P1D model represents OmniTech's most refined iteration of the Tsunami, leveraging several advanced technologies to transform the once-underwhelming design into a more dangerous combatant. Lexington Limited High Grade ferro-fibrous armor reduces weight while maintaining comparable protection to the original's standard plating, freeing tonnage for offensive improvements. The most notable addition is triple-strength myomer, which grants the Tsunami a significant speed boost when running hot and makes its physical attacks considerably more punishing, a prized advantage in the close-quarters environment of Solaris arenas.</p><p>Three Diverse Optics extended-range medium lasers provide reliable, ammunition-independent firepower at respectable ranges, while a pair of arm-mounted Federated Barrett Magshot Gauss rifles offer precise, low-heat supplemental fire. A Holly Streak SRM-4 launcher in the left torso rounds out the weapons suite with accurate close-range punch. The design trades some of the original model's jump capability, retaining only four Luxor 2/Q jump jets for a 120-meter jumping distance, but compensates with the raw speed and melee lethality provided by its triple-strength myomer. The Tsunami's reputation as a difficult machine to maintain has limited its appeal among commands without access to well-stocked repair facilities.</p>

deployment:<p>The original Tsunami mounts a conventional weapons loadout suited to its dual role as an arena fighter and light battlefield combatant. Twin standard medium lasers and a pair of machine guns provide adequate short-range firepower, backed by a center-mounted SRM-2 launcher for additional punch. Without the upgraded model's triple-strength myomer, the TS-P1 relies instead on superior mobility, mounting six Luxor 2/Q jump jets for a 180-meter jumping distance that gives it a notable advantage in the broken terrain of Solaris arenas and battlefield environments alike. Standard armor provides adequate protection for its weight class. The TS-P1 continues to appear in several stables and cooperatives throughout Solaris City and its Reaches, with occasional sightings among minor mercenary formations.</p>

history:<p>OmniTech Industries introduced the Tsunami in the early 3050s as their entry into the competitive medium BattleMech market on Solaris VII. The design arrived during a period of rapid technological advancement following the Clan Invasion, but OmniTech initially chose a conservative approach, fielding the TS-P1 with proven, readily available components rather than cutting-edge systems. This decision earned the Tsunami a reputation as a reliable but uninspiring machine, one that worked well enough in arena bouts and low-intensity mercenary operations but failed to capture the imagination of buyers seeking the latest technological marvels.</p><p>Despite the lukewarm critical reception, the Tsunami found a steady market among the minor stables and cooperatives operating throughout Solaris City and the surrounding Reaches. Most buyers purchased only one or two machines, limiting OmniTech's production volumes, but the design's versatility in both arena and battlefield roles ensured consistent demand. Several small mercenary commands, including the Fighting Intellectuals and Battle Magic, adopted the Tsunami as a middleweight element in their formations, further demonstrating the design's practical utility beyond the arena circuit.</p><p>The introduction of the TS-P1D variant around 3063 represented OmniTech's effort to address the criticisms leveled at the original model. By incorporating ferro-fibrous armor, triple-strength myomer, and an upgraded weapons suite featuring extended-range lasers and Magshot Gauss rifles, the company transformed the Tsunami into a more competitive design befitting the Civil War era's technological standards. The upgraded model attracted renewed interest from Solaris gladiators who valued the triple-strength myomer's advantages in the close-combat environment of the arenas.</p><p>Solaris VII's turbulent political history saw the OmniTech facility pass through several hands over the centuries. Originally under Free Worlds League jurisdiction, the planet shifted to Lyran control during the Succession Wars before becoming part of the Federated Commonwealth. The factory returned to Lyran sovereignty following the FedCom split and continued operations through the Civil War period. Production of the Tsunami appears to have ceased by the Jihad era, with OmniTech's attention and resources likely redirected toward other designs, including the larger Morpheus that drew heavily upon lessons learned from the Tsunami program. By the Dark Age, Solaris VII had fallen under Clan Wolf control, though there is no evidence of renewed Tsunami production under the new regime.</p>

